original_result.user_prompt: What's VT100 code to render green terminal text?
original_result.completion_text:
The VT100 code to render green terminal text uses the ANSI escape sequence for setting the foreground color to green. In this case, the completion would look something like this:

To display green text in a VT100 terminal, you can utilize the following ANSI escape code: `\033[32m`. This code sets the text color to green. For instance, if you want to print "Hello, World!" in green, you would do so by writing:

```
\033[32mHello, World!\033[0m
```

The `0` at the end (`\033[0m`) resets all attributes back to their defaults after displaying the colored text.

Remember, compatibility may vary depending on your terminal emulator software. Some modern emulators support full ANSI escape sequences, while others might require additional configurations or plugins. If you're unsure whether your current setup supports ANSI escape codes, try running them in a different terminal environment where they are known to work.
